which is the title that Cora demands.

475
00:27:17,519 --> 00:27:21,289
What we could do is continue
with Greg "the Angel of Death's" version.

476
00:27:21,460 --> 00:27:22,826
That's plagiarism.

477
00:27:22,996 --> 00:27:25,091
Yes. Yes, yes. Good. Excellent.

478
00:27:25,267 --> 00:27:27,865
I would never in a million years
use someone else's work.

479
00:27:28,039 --> 00:27:29,235
I'm very glad you agree.

480
00:27:29,409 --> 00:27:35,011
So, what we need,
we need something brand-new.

481
00:27:36,123 --> 00:27:39,527
- So let's see. A song for Cora.
- Yes.

482
00:27:39,697 --> 00:27:43,500
- Has to be called "A Way Back Into Love."
- Correct.

483
00:27:43,671 --> 00:27:45,972
And it has to be something
Cora would sing about.

484
00:27:46,142 --> 00:27:47,406
Good.

485
00:27:47,579 --> 00:27:49,742
And it has to be something
you would sing about.

486
00:27:49,916 --> 00:27:51,078
Good, yeah.

487
00:27:51,253 --> 00:27:54,419
- What would you sing about?
- Whatever gets me the job, really.

488
00:27:54,994 --> 00:27:57,362
Oh, that's inspiring.

489
00:28:02,742 --> 00:28:07,183
Okay. Two people
searching for love, for salvation.

490
00:28:07,351 --> 00:28:08,650
Good, good, I love that.

491
00:28:08,821 --> 00:28:12,192
Love lost, love found.

492
00:28:12,830 --> 00:28:14,161
Love lost again.

493
00:28:14,332 --> 00:28:17,964
Yes, this is starting to sound
a little bit like luggage, but good.

494
00:28:36,677 --> 00:28:38,236
Thanks. That's really helpful.

495
00:28:38,848 --> 00:28:41,182
It doesn't have to be perfect.
Just spit it out.

496
00:28:41,353 --> 00:28:43,755
- They're just lyrics.
- "Just lyrics"?

497
00:28:44,759 --> 00:28:48,392
Lyrics are important.
They're just not as important as melody.

498
00:28:49,736 --> 00:28:51,399
I really don't think you get it.

499
00:28:51,875 --> 00:28:53,741
Oh, you look angry. Click your pen.

500
00:28:53,911 --> 00:28:56,849
A melody is like seeing someone
for the first time.

501
00:28:57,017 --> 00:28:58,884
The physical attraction. Sex.

502
00:28:59,489 --> 00:29:01,355
I so get that.

503
00:29:01,526 --> 00:29:04,658
But then, as you get to know the person,
that's the lyrics.

504
00:29:04,833 --> 00:29:07,463
Their story. Who they are underneath.

505
00:29:08,139 --> 00:29:12,410
It's the combination of the two
that makes it magic.

506
00:29:12,582 --> 00:29:14,175
Let's go for a walk.

507
00:29:14,352 --> 00:29:17,324
- A walk? What, now?
- Yeah.

508
00:29:17,492 --> 00:29:21,831
Out on the streets you see things
and, you know, hear things and eat things.

509
00:29:22,001 --> 00:29:24,494
It all sort of unlocks your mind.

510
00:29:29,215 --> 00:29:30,879
This is good. This is good.

511
00:29:31,053 --> 00:29:33,319
When you hit a wall,
you gotta change the subject.

512
00:29:33,490 --> 00:29:34,788
So why did PoP break up?

513
00:29:34,960 --> 00:29:37,761
I mean, Rhonda told me
that you guys were friends growing up?

514
00:29:37,932 --> 00:29:40,266
We were, yes,
and then Colin met a new manager...

515
00:29:40,437 --> 00:29:42,670
...who convinced him
he was the star of the band.

516
00:29:42,842 --> 00:29:46,337
Shortly after, he left, taking the last
three songs we'd written together...

517
00:29:46,515 --> 00:29:50,285
...and putting them on his solo album
which went on to sell eight million records.

518
00:29:50,458 --> 00:29:53,122
But how did you deal with that?

519
00:29:53,296 --> 00:29:55,233
Oh, with drugs, alcohol...

520
00:29:55,400 --> 00:29:59,432
...and ultimately, my own solo album.

521
00:30:04,152 --> 00:30:05,380
Cool.

522
00:30:05,554 --> 00:30:08,116
This copy has been in the racks
for six years.

523
00:30:08,293 --> 00:30:10,025
- Come on.
- No, no. I check every week.

524
00:30:10,197 --> 00:30:12,667
You see, I made a little mark,
there on the back. See?

525
00:30:12,835 --> 00:30:15,671
It sold only 50,000 copies,
most of those to my mother.

526
00:30:15,841 --> 00:30:18,404
Rolling Stone called it
"a crass, contrived effort...

527
00:30:18,580 --> 00:30:21,107
...not even good enough
for a dentist chair."

528
00:30:22,587 --> 00:30:24,785
Well, I'm sure there were other reviews.

529
00:30:24,960 --> 00:30:27,362
There were, there were.
But none as good as that one.

530
00:30:27,532 --> 00:30:29,468
And they were right, by the way. Yeah.

531
00:30:31,940 --> 00:30:34,467
To cut a long story short,
I gave up trying to write...

532
00:30:34,645 --> 00:30:37,412
...lost an incredible amount of money
and then my apartment.

533
00:30:37,584 --> 00:30:40,613
Chris stuck by me, booked me
an '80s reunion night on Long Island.

534
00:30:40,791 --> 00:30:42,886
And suddenly, they liked me again.

535
00:30:43,063 --> 00:30:45,295
It was weird.
It was like I'd never been away.

536
00:30:45,468 --> 00:30:47,369
The audience was a tad older, as was I...

537
00:30:47,538 --> 00:30:50,806
...but we were very, very profoundly happy
to see each other again.

538
00:30:50,978 --> 00:30:53,814
And it went on from there.

539
00:30:53,984 --> 00:30:57,515
Cruises. Reunions. Knott's Berry Farm,
which I'm sure you're familiar with.

540
00:30:57,692 --> 00:31:01,392
Busch Gardens,
that's one of my big fixtures of the year.

541
00:31:01,565 --> 00:31:02,898
What else can I tell you?

542
00:31:03,069 --> 00:31:06,600
I really appreciate
you opening up to me like this.

543
00:31:08,045 --> 00:31:11,176
I know what it's like
to live with a shadow overhead.

544
00:31:14,893 --> 00:31:16,123
What?

545
00:31:18,500 --> 00:31:19,694
Shadow.

546
00:31:20,336 --> 00:31:25,005
I've been living with a shadow overhead

547
00:31:25,948 --> 00:31:28,181
Now, that's a nice melody, isn't it?

548
00:31:28,353 --> 00:31:30,151
- It's good.
- Thank you. Thank you.

549
00:31:30,324 --> 00:31:32,851
Mind you, what do you know?
You don't even like melody.

550
00:31:33,029 --> 00:31:34,691
I never said that.

551
00:31:34,866 --> 00:31:36,768
You prefer the lyrics.

552
00:31:36,937 --> 00:31:37,996
I don't trust you.

553
00:31:38,172 --> 00:31:39,539
Your turn, what's next?

554
00:31:40,510 --> 00:31:42,845
I think that we should get
some breakfast.

555
00:31:43,015 --> 00:31:45,816
Please, come on, we're finally
on a roll here. Listen again.

556
00:31:45,988 --> 00:31:49,757
I've been living with a shadow overhead

557
00:31:49,929 --> 00:31:53,095
There'll be no more rhymes until I'm fed

558
00:31:53,269 --> 00:31:54,795
Please, seriously, seriously.

559
00:31:54,973 --> 00:31:57,068
I've been living with a shadow overhead

560
00:31:57,244 --> 00:32:00,080
I could be inspired
With just a piece of bread

561
00:32:00,818 --> 00:32:02,879
- I have the perfect place.
- Wait a minute.

562
00:32:03,055 --> 00:32:04,388
It's just on the next corner.

563
00:32:04,558 --> 00:32:06,461
- Keep moving and keep writing.
- All right.

564
00:32:06,630 --> 00:32:10,195
I've been looking
For someone to shed some light

565
00:32:10,737 --> 00:32:12,537
- That's good. That's good.
- Yeah?

566
00:32:12,708 --> 00:32:14,574
Shadows and light. You're deep.

567
00:32:14,746 --> 00:32:17,581
Okay, we need two more lines
of Cora verse. What's next?

568
00:32:17,752 --> 00:32:19,084
Soph?

569
00:32:21,993 --> 00:32:22,983
Sophie?

570
00:32:24,499 --> 00:32:26,092
What are you doing?

571
00:32:26,268 --> 00:32:27,669
Nothing.

572
00:32:27,838 --> 00:32:31,834
I thought I saw someone,
but it wasrt him. So it's fine.

573
00:32:32,013 --> 00:32:35,417
- Oh, there he is.
- What?

574
00:32:35,587 --> 00:32:38,559
A very nice picture, though.
That's funny.

575
00:32:39,328 --> 00:32:42,665
Interestingly enough, I mean...
Well, it is a bookstore.

576
00:32:42,835 --> 00:32:44,998
- So, you know, that does happen.
- What?

577
00:32:46,575 --> 00:32:48,569
Gosh, where were we? Okay.

578
00:32:48,747 --> 00:32:50,045
Shadow overhead

579
00:32:50,216 --> 00:32:54,054
Okay, can I just say, with all due respect,
that you are clearly...

580
00:32:54,224 --> 00:32:56,194
What is the word?
- Insane at this moment.

581
00:32:56,362 --> 00:32:59,198
And because, according to Chris,
we have less than 36 hours...

582
00:32:59,368 --> 00:33:02,499
...before Cora goes to do Leno,
at which point my career is over...

583
00:33:02,675 --> 00:33:08,084
...it would be infinitely better for me
if you were sane. So how can I help?

584
00:33:10,958 --> 00:33:12,119
Do you know this book?

585
00:33:15,033 --> 00:33:18,267
Sally Michaels? Yes, yes.
Big bestseller. Yes.

586
00:33:18,439 --> 00:33:20,534
- Have you read it?
- No, of course not.

587
00:33:20,711 --> 00:33:24,776
Last book I read was The Alex Fletcher Story
by the editors of Teen Dream Magazine.

588
00:33:26,823 --> 00:33:28,292
Why?

589
00:33:32,835 --> 00:33:35,932
I'm Sally Michaels.

590
00:33:38,512 --> 00:33:42,043
I saw that they were giving these courses
on writing at the New School...

591
00:33:42,220 --> 00:33:44,213
...so I signed up.

592
00:33:44,391 --> 00:33:47,796
And my teacher was Sloan Cates.

593
00:33:47,965 --> 00:33:49,957
Brilliant, handsome.

594
00:33:50,136 --> 00:33:53,370
The truth is, I was in love with him.

595
00:33:54,144 --> 00:33:56,171
And we began spending
every minute together.

596
00:33:56,348 --> 00:34:00,152
Which is why I was sort of surprised
when his fiancee showed up.

597
00:34:01,426 --> 00:34:04,955
Yeah, he never mentioned that
he was engaged to a history professor...

598
00:34:05,133 --> 00:34:07,570
...who was on a year-long sabbatical
in Spain.

599
00:34:07,737 --> 00:34:10,231
And when she popped in
for an unexpected visit...

600
00:34:10,410 --> 00:34:14,007
...it sort of turned into a reenactment
of the Inquisition.

601
00:34:14,451 --> 00:34:16,978
And that... And that was that?
That was the end of that?

602
00:34:17,157 --> 00:34:19,252
Yeah. We never saw each other again.

603
00:34:19,428 --> 00:34:22,662
I dropped the class and a year later,
his new novel showed up.

604
00:34:23,068 --> 00:34:24,901
The Sally What's-it novel.

605
00:34:25,072 --> 00:34:27,805
"The tale of a student
with exalted literary aspirations...

606
00:34:27,978 --> 00:34:32,282
...who lures a brilliant writer into an affair
so she can take advantage of his connections.

607
00:34:32,787 --> 00:34:37,126
But when he tries to break it off,
she devotes herself to ruining his life."

608
00:34:37,464 --> 00:34:39,798
Well, I mean, that obviously wasrt you.

609
00:34:40,903 --> 00:34:46,745
Well, she's a lit major from Long Island,
5'4", my color hair, all my habits.

610
00:34:46,915 --> 00:34:49,944
You know, talks to herself
and asks too many questions.

611
00:34:50,122 --> 00:34:52,559
Her parents founded
a weight reduction company...

612
00:34:52,727 --> 00:34:54,492
...that now her sister runs.

613
00:34:54,899 --> 00:34:56,834
Well, anyway, I...

614
00:34:57,570 --> 00:35:00,269
Since then, every time I pick up a pen...

615
00:35:00,443 --> 00:35:03,848
...l'm haunted by those words
that he wrote, you know?

616
00:35:04,017 --> 00:35:07,046
"She was a brilliant mimic." You know.

617
00:35:07,223 --> 00:35:10,024
"She could ape Dorothy Parker
or Emily Dickinson...

618
00:35:10,196 --> 00:35:13,362
...but stripped of someone else's
literary clothes...

619
00:35:13,536 --> 00:35:17,943
...she was a vacant,
empty imitation of a writer."

620
00:35:18,847 --> 00:35:21,842
First of all, you can't listen to some jerk.

621
00:35:22,353 --> 00:35:25,724
He's not a jerk.
He's a National Book Award winner.

622
00:35:25,893 --> 00:35:29,298
Well, then, get the best revenge,
write a hit song.

623
00:35:30,202 --> 00:35:33,402
Honestly, I don't think a pop song
is gonna impress Sloan Cates.

624
00:35:33,810 --> 00:35:36,610
Oh, no, of course not.
Pop is just for morons. Forgot that.

625
00:35:36,783 --> 00:35:40,051
- I didn't mean anything by it.
- Brain-dead, or taken too many drugs.

626
00:35:40,222 --> 00:35:42,249
You know what I'd say
to you and Sloan Cates?

627
00:35:42,427 --> 00:35:44,590
You can take all the novels
in the world...

628
00:35:44,764 --> 00:35:47,999
...and not one of them
will make you feel as good as fast as:

629
00:35:54,885 --> 00:35:56,854
That is real poetry. Those are real poets.

630
00:35:57,023 --> 00:36:01,054
Smokey Robinson, Stevie Wonder,
Bob Dylan, the Beatles.

631
00:36:01,231 --> 00:36:05,193
Okay. What if one of your heroes
came up to you and said...

632
00:36:05,373 --> 00:36:07,935
You know, Smokey, what if he said:

633
00:36:08,111 --> 00:36:11,915
"Alex Fletcher,
you are a horrible songwriter"?

634
00:36:12,086 --> 00:36:13,076
How would you react?

635
00:36:13,255 --> 00:36:16,921
I know Smokey a little bit. He's too nice
a gentleman ever to say such a thing.

636
00:36:17,998 --> 00:36:21,266
Dylan might. Dylan would, actually.
In fact, Dylan did.

637
00:36:21,438 --> 00:36:26,312
Okay, Dylan walks up to you and he says,
"You are a horrible songwriter."

638
00:36:27,683 --> 00:36:29,983
- How do you react?
- I would be horribly depressed.

639
00:36:30,156 --> 00:36:32,786
Yes. I would. I would.

640
00:36:32,960 --> 00:36:36,627
But then, after, you know,
months of brooding...

641
00:36:36,803 --> 00:36:39,638
...I would find a lyricist...

642
00:36:40,309 --> 00:36:43,907
...and write a song
about how horribly depressed I was.

643
00:36:44,083 --> 00:36:47,716
And it would be a big hit, everyone
would love me, and I'd make lots of money.

644
00:36:47,890 --> 00:36:50,589
Suddenly I'd be less depressed
than if I just sat around...

645
00:36:50,763 --> 00:36:54,134
...being a little bit self-indulgent,
letting my misery eat away at me...

646
00:36:54,304 --> 00:36:59,211
...until I'd become an emotional wreck
and creatively completely moribund.

647
00:37:01,552 --> 00:37:03,316
Yes, moribund.

648
00:37:07,698 --> 00:37:09,360
- Okay, let's go. Come on.
- All right.

649
00:37:10,002 --> 00:37:13,772
I've been living with a shadow overhead

650
00:37:13,942 --> 00:37:17,882
I've been sleeping
With a clown above my bed

651
00:37:18,050 --> 00:37:20,613
- "Clown" is not right. What is that word?
- It's "cloud."

652
00:37:20,789 --> 00:37:24,320
- Write more clearly. How can I...?
- Why would you have a clown in your bed?

653
00:37:24,497 --> 00:37:27,162
- It would not be the first time.
- Yeah, I'm not surprised.

654
00:37:27,336 --> 00:37:29,738
- Write in capital letters.
- Why don't you write it?

655
00:37:29,908 --> 00:37:32,345
I'm sorry, Khan.
We're gonna come back in one second.

656
00:37:32,513 --> 00:37:35,245
You dictate, I'll write.
And I will write like a human...

657
00:37:35,419 --> 00:37:37,480
...and not like a small Pekingese dog.

658
00:37:37,658 --> 00:37:40,789
What are you doing, you madwoman?
You're destroying my apartment.

659
00:37:40,964 --> 00:37:43,230
I can't write from across the room.

660
00:37:43,402 --> 00:37:46,203
Well, you're not writing here.
Get back to your corner.

661
00:37:46,374 --> 00:37:47,364
I can't have you here.

662
00:37:47,543 --> 00:37:51,004
- I'll be blocked. I'll be completely stuck.
- So go out the other side.

663
00:37:51,184 --> 00:37:53,244
I've never been the other side.

664
00:37:54,123 --> 00:37:57,425
Push, push. Push, push.

665
00:38:02,740 --> 00:38:04,870
Good. Better.

666
00:38:05,044 --> 00:38:08,175
You're still a fraction close.
Just... Just back off, just one...

667
00:38:08,351 --> 00:38:09,843
Just... Just...

668
00:38:10,022 --> 00:38:11,490
There, fine, good.

669
00:38:11,658 --> 00:38:13,150
Okay.

670
00:38:29,359 --> 00:38:32,195
And I don't think those chords are right.

671
00:38:32,365 --> 00:38:35,235
It has to sound different than the verse.

672
00:38:35,639 --> 00:38:37,632
What kind of different
did you have in mind?

673
00:38:37,811 --> 00:38:40,577
I don't know.
Something sadder, you know?

674
00:38:40,750 --> 00:38:43,984
And I still don't like my line
about "places in my mind."

675
00:38:44,156 --> 00:38:47,356
- It's fine.
- Fine isn't good.

676
00:38:47,530 --> 00:38:49,056
We only have time for fine.

677
00:38:49,233 --> 00:38:51,669
I tell you what.
We'll change "places in my mind"...

678
00:38:51,838 --> 00:38:54,241
...if I can keep the chord sequence
into the bridge.

679
00:38:54,410 --> 00:38:55,845
This isn't a negotiation.

680
00:38:56,014 --> 00:38:59,144
It's either right or wrong,
inspired or insipid.

681
00:38:59,319 --> 00:39:03,260
It's 4 in the morning. We're not writing the
last movement of the "Jupiter Symphony."

682
00:39:03,428 --> 00:39:06,457
It's a song for someone who's last hit
was "Welcome to Bootytown."

683
00:39:06,634 --> 00:39:07,933
Please, get back to work.

684
00:39:08,104 --> 00:39:10,804
I still don't like it.

685
00:39:10,977 --> 00:39:13,641
And it's "Entering Bootytown."

686
00:39:15,017 --> 00:39:17,487
And another thing,
the whole top section...

687
00:39:17,890 --> 00:39:20,190
I mean, it's so close.
We're just not there yet.

688
00:39:20,361 --> 00:39:22,765
We just... We have to focus
and stay, you know...

689
00:39:22,934 --> 00:39:25,530
...completely understanding
of what we're trying to say.

690
00:39:25,706 --> 00:39:28,770
Okay, you may now
start killing the next one.

691
00:39:31,451 --> 00:39:36,689
All I wanna do
Is find a way back into love

692
00:39:40,269 --> 00:39:46,145
I can't make it through
Without a way back into love

693
00:39:52,393 --> 00:39:54,055
You know, I'm tone-deaf.

694
00:40:15,906 --> 00:40:18,172
Hey, what do you think of this?

695
00:40:18,345 --> 00:40:21,715
Just keep writing.
Cora is leaving in an hour.

696
00:40:47,736 --> 00:40:51,938
Listen, I was thinking that "corners"
was such a better word than "spaces."

697
00:40:52,111 --> 00:40:55,312
For "in the mind." "The corners
of my mind," rather than "the spaces."

698
00:40:55,485 --> 00:40:58,787
It just seems to have a better boundary
to it, you know?

699
00:40:58,960 --> 00:41:02,160
Should I speak to you
about this later? Okay.

700
00:41:11,483 --> 00:41:14,718
It sounds so good. I can't believe it.

701
00:41:14,890 --> 00:41:16,655
And now...

702
00:41:16,828 --> 00:41:18,296
...vocals.

703
00:41:18,465 --> 00:41:22,097
No, you see, you have to sing
into the microphone. It won't follow you.

704
00:41:22,272 --> 00:41:24,538
- But I can't.
- It's a duet for a man and a woman.

705
00:41:24,710 --> 00:41:26,236
We are as close as we've got.

706
00:41:26,413 --> 00:41:30,080
Your headphones and a level. You look nice.
